# API Rules

References:

- docs/api-specification.md
- docs/coding-standards.md
- docs/user-flows.md

---

# API Design Principles

All APIs must be:

- Consistent
- Predictable
- RESTful
- Versioned

Never create custom patterns when a REST pattern already exists.

---

# API Versioning

All endpoints must use versioning.

Pattern:

```text
/api/v1/
```

Examples:

```text
/api/v1/auth/google-login
/api/v1/dashboard
/api/v1/orders
/api/v1/withdrawals
```

---

# REST Conventions

Create Resource

```http
POST /api/v1/orders
```

Get Resource

```http
GET /api/v1/orders/{id}
```

List Resources

```http
GET /api/v1/orders
```

Update Resource

```http
PUT /api/v1/orders/{id}
```

Delete Resource

```http
DELETE /api/v1/orders/{id}
```

---

Forbidden

```http
POST /GetOrders
POST /DeleteOrder
POST /CreateWithdrawal
```

---

# Controller Naming

Controllers must end with:

```text
Controller
```

Examples:

```text
AuthController
OrdersController
WithdrawalsController
```

---

# Route Naming

Use lowercase.

Use kebab-case if needed.

Good:

```text
/api/v1/affiliate-links
/api/v1/withdrawals
```

Bad:

```text
/api/v1/AffiliateLinks
/api/v1/GetWithdrawals
```

---

# Request Models

Every endpoint requiring input must have a Request DTO.

Example:

```csharp
GenerateAffiliateLinkRequest
CreateWithdrawalRequest
```

Never accept Entity objects directly.

---

# Response Models

Every endpoint must return Response DTOs.

Examples:

```csharp
DashboardResponse
OrderResponse
WithdrawalResponse
```

Never return Entity objects.

---

# Standard Response Wrapper

All APIs must use a standard response structure.

Success:

```json
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {}
}
```

Failure:

```json
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Validation failed"
}
```

---

# HTTP Status Codes

Success

```http
200 OK
201 Created
204 No Content
```

Client Errors

```http
400 Bad Request
401 Unauthorized
403 Forbidden
404 Not Found
409 Conflict
```

Server Errors

```http
500 Internal Server Error
```

---

# Validation Rules

Input validation must use FluentValidation.

Invalid requests return:

```http
400 Bad Request
```

Validation errors must be user-friendly.

---

# Authentication Rules

Protected endpoints require:

```csharp
[Authorize]
```

Admin endpoints require:

```csharp
[Authorize(Roles = "Admin")]
```

Never trust client role information.

---

# Pagination Rules

List endpoints must support pagination.

Parameters:

```http
?page=1&pageSize=20
```

Response:

```json
{
  "items": [],
  "page": 1,
  "pageSize": 20,
  "totalItems": 100,
  "totalPages": 5
}
```

---

# Filtering Rules

Filtering should use query parameters.

Example:

```http
GET /api/v1/orders?status=approved
```

Avoid custom filter endpoints.

---

# Sorting Rules

Sorting should use query parameters.

Example:

```http
GET /api/v1/orders?sortBy=createdAt&direction=desc
```

---

# Security Rules

Never expose:

- Internal IDs not meant for clients
- Database schema details
- Stack traces
- Exception details

---

# Idempotency Rules

Critical financial endpoints should support idempotency where applicable.

Examples:

- Withdrawal processing
- Webhook processing

Prevent duplicate execution.

---

# Webhook Rules

Webhook endpoints:

- Must validate signatures
- Must validate source
- Must be idempotent

Examples:

```text
/api/v1/webhooks/accesstrade
```

---

# Health Check Endpoint

Required:

```http
GET /api/v1/health
```

Response:

```json
{
  "success": true
}
```

---

# Swagger Rules

Swagger enabled:

- Development
- Staging

Swagger disabled:

- Production

---

# API Documentation Rules

Whenever an endpoint is added:

Verify if updates are required in:

- api-specification.md
- user-flows.md

---

# Code Generation Checklist

✓ RESTful

✓ Versioned

✓ DTOs used

✓ Response wrapper used

✓ Status codes correct

✓ Validation exists

✓ Authentication applied

✓ Pagination supported

✓ No entities exposed

✓ API spec remains consistent
